Ultrasonic Sensor Controlled Servo

This project uses an ultrasonic sensor to control a servo motor. The servo position is mapped based on the distance measured by the sensor, and the travel time is printed to the Serial Monitor.

This project helps beginners learn:

Reading an ultrasonic sensor with pulseIn

Mapping sensor values to servo positions

Controlling a servo motor with the Servo library

Using Serial Monitor for debugging

Arduino Code
#include <Servo.h>

// Ultrasonic sensor pins
int trigPin = 12;
int echoPin = 11;
int travelTime;

// Servo
int servoPin = 5;
int position;
Servo myServo;

void setup() {
  // Initialize ultrasonic sensor pins
  pinMode(trigPin, OUTPUT);
  pinMode(echoPin, INPUT);

  // Attach servo
  myServo.attach(servoPin);

  // Start serial communication
  Serial.begin(9600);
}

void loop() {
  // Trigger ultrasonic sensor
  digitalWrite(trigPin, LOW);
  delayMicroseconds(10);
  digitalWrite(trigPin, HIGH);
  delayMicroseconds(10);
  digitalWrite(trigPin, LOW);

  // Read pulse duration
  travelTime = pulseIn(echoPin, HIGH);
  delay(25);
  Serial.println(travelTime);

  // Map travel time to servo position
  position = (165.0 * travelTime - 66000.0) / 3400.0;
  myServo.write(position);

  // Safety limits for servo
  if (travelTime > 3800 || travelTime < 400) {
    myServo.write(90); // Default middle position
  }
}

Circuit Setup

Components needed:

Arduino Uno (or compatible board)

1 × Ultrasonic sensor (HC-SR04 or similar)

1 × Servo motor

Breadboard

Jumper wires

Wiring Instructions:
Ultrasonic Sensor 
Trig → pin 12
Echo → pin 11
VCC → 5V
GND → GND

Servo
Signal → pin 5
Power → 5V
GND → GND

How it works:
The ultrasonic sensor measures the distance to an object.
The servo position is calculated based on the travel time of the ultrasonic pulse.
Safety checks keep the servo at 90° if the object is too close or too far.
The Serial Monitor prints the travel time of the pulse for debugging.
